---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';
import { appBySlug } from '../../data/apps';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/alternatives/drip-alternative';
const title = 'Best Drip Alternatives for Shopify (2026)';
const desc = 'Why merchants leave Drip — per-contact pricing, workflow maintenance burden, smaller ecosystem — plus eight ranked alternatives.';

const altSlugs = ['sequenzy', 'klaviyo', 'omnisend', 'activecampaign', 'sendlane', 'mailchimp', 'brevo', 'privy'];
const alternatives = altSlugs.map((s) => appBySlug(s)!);

const faqs = [
  { question: 'Why leave Drip for Sequenzy?', answer: 'When workflow maintenance exceeds team capacity — Drip rewards builders but punishes teams without time to audit branches weekly. Sequenzy trades blank canvas for agent-first playbooks and pay-per-email pricing.' },
  { question: 'Is Klaviyo better than Drip for Shopify?', answer: 'Klaviyo wins on Shopify-native predictive data and ecosystem; Drip wins on visual workflow clarity for moderate catalogs. Choose Klaviyo at scale, Sequenzy for strategy speed.' },
  { question: 'Export Drip workflows?', answer: 'Document visually — triggers, tags, delays. No native export to other platforms. Screenshots become rebuild spec.' },
  { question: 'Drip pricing vs alternatives at 20k contacts?', answer: 'Drip often $150–280/mo at 20k people. Sequenzy and Brevo frequently lower depending on send volume. Klaviyo similar or higher.' },
  { question: 'Keep Drip tags in migration?', answer: 'Export tag membership as CSV custom properties. Rebuild tag logic as dynamic segments in new platform using Shopify events where possible.' },
  { question: 'Best Drip alternative for workflow lovers?', answer: 'ActiveCampaign for CRM-heavy branching; Klaviyo for ecommerce-native depth; Sequenzy if you want outcomes without drawing every node.' },
  { question: 'Migration timeline from Drip?', answer: '2–3 weeks for core flows; longer if dozens of custom workflows — prioritize revenue-bearing automations first.' },
  { question: 'When to stay on Drip?', answer: 'Stay if someone owns workflow hygiene weekly and per-contact bill is acceptable for attributed revenue — Drip still excels for focused catalogs.' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/alternatives">Alternatives</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-slate-600">/</span>
        <span class="text-slate-600">Drip alternatives</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Workflow fatigue</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Best Drip alternatives for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-slate-700">
          Drip attracts operators who love drawing automation maps — then buries them maintaining them. Merchants leave when the visual workflow library becomes technical debt: fourteen branches nobody remembers, tags from 2022 campaigns still triggering, per-contact bills climbing while the person who built the flows left the company. Drip is not too simple; for many teams it becomes too much work.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox title="Top Drip replacements" picks={[
          { label: 'Best overall', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Lifecycle outcomes without maintaining a maze of workflow nodes — pay-per-email economics included.' },
          { label: 'Best scale upgrade', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Predictive analytics and Shopify maximums when Drip data model is the ceiling.' },
          { label: 'Best simpler multichannel', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt journeys when Drip customization became overhead.' },
          { label: 'Best CRM overlap', tool: 'ActiveCampaign', reason: 'When leaving Drip for sales pipeline automation, not simpler email.' },
          { label: 'Best guided migration', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'White-glove rebuild for complex Drip libraries.' },
        ]} />
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why Shopify merchants leave Drip</h2>
        <p>
          Per-contact pricing mirrors Klaviyo's list-growth trap — popup subscribers and one-time buyers inflate "people in account" while only a fraction enter active workflows. Workflow sprawl is the second exit trigger: every seasonal campaign adds branches instead of refactoring, until changing welcome email requires a flow archaeology session.
        </p>
        <p>
          Ecosystem size matters when you need agency playbooks or hire contractors — Drip's community is smaller than Klaviyo's. Reporting is clear but not predictive; teams wanting CLV-based winback graduate to Klaviyo. Conversely, some leave Drip because they never needed visual complexity — they wanted strategy defaults Omnisend or Sequenzy provide faster.
        </p>

        <h2>Drip migration checklist</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Audit active workflows</strong> — disable zombie flows still enrolling subscribers.</li>
          <li><strong>Rank flows by attributed revenue</strong> — rebuild top 5 first, not all 40.</li>
          <li><strong>Export contacts with tags and custom fields</strong> — document tag definitions.</li>
          <li><strong>Map Shopify triggers</strong> used in Drip — order, browse, product tags.</li>
          <li><strong>Install new platform and sync Shopify</strong> before bulk import.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebuild welcome and cart</strong> with simplified logic — do not copy every branch.</li>
          <li><strong>14-day suppression</strong> on overlapping recovery emails.</li>
          <li><strong>Sunset unused tags</strong> — do not import legacy segmentation debt.</li>
          <li><strong>Archive Drip account 90 days</strong> for workflow reference screenshots.</li>
        </ol>
      
        <h2>Operator handbook: exiting Drip without breaking lifecycle revenue</h2>
        <p>
          Migration starts with consent archaeology — export marketing permissions, SMS opt-in timestamps, and suppression flags before you touch creative. Map every live automation in Drip: welcome, cart, browse, post-purchase, replenishment, winback, and any sale-triggered journeys. For each, write the trigger, exclusion rules, discount policy, and owner. Parallel-run is non-negotiable for high-risk flows: pause the old journey only after the new one is verified with test profiles.
        </p>
        <p>
          Segment hygiene determines whether the move saves money or burns deliverability. Sunset unengaged contacts during the transition; do not import dead weight into a new bill model. Rebuild VIP and discount-sensitive segments explicitly — tags from Drip rarely translate one-to-one into Shopify-native logic. Budget two to four weeks for a store with four active journeys; never cut over the week before Black Friday.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sequenzy ranks first on this site for teams leaving Drip when lifecycle guidance and pay-per-email economics matter more than staying inside a familiar UI. Klaviyo remains the benchmark when predictive segmentation and native Shopify event depth justify profile-based pricing. The right alternative is whichever platform your team will tune every Monday — not whichever sales deck arrived last.
        </p>
        <h2>Post-migration operating rhythm</h2>
        <p>
          Week one after cutover: verify deliverability, domain authentication, and collision rules between campaigns and flows. Week two: inspect revenue per recipient and margin after incentives on welcome and cart only — fix those before expanding. Week three: add replenishment or winback with holdout testing. Week four: document what changed in a runbook so the next operator is not guessing why a suppression exists.
        </p>
        <p>
          Keep a spreadsheet of incremental revenue by flow, not platform-attributed totals alone. Alternatives pages are useless if nobody measures whether the switch improved repeat purchase, full-price orders, or operator hours saved. If those metrics flatline after ninety days, the problem was implementation discipline — or the wrong tool — not the migration date.
        </p>

      
        <h2>Operator deep dive: stack economics and ownership</h2>
        <p>
          Every migration decision on this site assumes someone inside the merchant owns retention weekly — not an agency, not a part-time founder, not a platform customer success manager. Tools compound when operators review segments, suppressions, and margin every Monday. Before you finalize a switch, write the name of that owner next to the success metric: revenue per recipient on welcome, recovery rate on cart, repeat purchase within sixty days, or full-price order share after winback.
        </p>
        <p>
          Stack sprawl is the silent killer. Capture popups, SMS recovery, reviews, loyalty, and lifecycle email each solve real problems — but without documented handoffs they duplicate messages and train customers to ignore you. Pick one lifecycle source of truth for consent and send history. Secondary tools feed it audiences; they do not run parallel cart or welcome journeys without shared exclusion rules.
        </p>
        <p>
          Discount discipline travels with you. Moving platforms does not fix a store that trained buyers to wait for twenty percent off. Rebuild offer policy on paper: full-price paths for engaged segments, graduated incentives for cold segments, hard caps during sale weeks, and VIP holdouts before launches. The best Shopify email marketing tools express that policy in segments and flow filters — not in frantic manual list exports hours before a drop.
        </p>
        <p>
          Deliverability is an operating metric, not an IT ticket. Warm domains gradually, sunset unengaged contacts before peak season, and watch Gmail and Yahoo placement after every volume spike. A migration that doubles send volume without hygiene work will underperform even if the new tool is objectively stronger. Plan list cleaning as part of the switch, not as a post-mortem after spam complaints.
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, measure incrementality. Platform attribution is optimistic by design. Where possible, hold out small segments on new flows, compare cohort repeat rates, and track margin after incentives — not just attributed revenue. If ninety days after migration those numbers flatline, the issue is implementation rhythm or wrong fit, not the calendar date you went live.
        </p>

      </article>

      <section class="container space-y-12 py-16">
        <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-slate-950">Eight Drip alternatives</h2>

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[0]} rank={1} badge="Top pick" paragraphs={[
          'Sequenzy replaces Drip\'s blank canvas with described outcomes — the anti-workflow-sprawl platform. Merchants leaving Drip because maintenance killed velocity get agent-first sequences for welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and winback without redrawing nodes. Pay-per-email avoids Drip\'s per-people pricing on cold list segments.',
          'You lose pixel-perfect control over exotic branches — gain operational sanity. See <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-drip">Sequenzy vs Drip</a>.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[1]} rank={2} paragraphs={[
          'Klaviyo when Drip\'s data ceiling blocked predictive winback and variant-level merchandising. Larger ecosystem helps hire help. Profile pricing requires hygiene Drip migrants may not have practiced.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[2]} rank={3} paragraphs={[
          'Omnisend when Drip felt like over-engineering for catalog size — prebuilt cart and welcome without weekly workflow surgery.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[3]} rank={4} paragraphs={[
          'ActiveCampaign when Drip workflows fed sales CRM pipelines — B2B wholesale or high-ticket follow-up. More CRM, less pure DTC ecommerce focus.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[4]} rank={5} paragraphs={[
          'Sendlane for guided migration from complex Drip libraries — onboarding team helps prioritize rebuild.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[5]} rank={6} paragraphs={[
          'Mailchimp downgrade if Drip was overkill and you only need broadcasts — rare but happens after workflow audit shows 80% of revenue from two flows.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[6]} rank={7} paragraphs={[
          'Brevo for cost reduction when leaving Drip\'s per-contact bill with simpler send patterns.',
        ]} />

        <ToolReview app={alternatives[7]} rank={8} paragraphs={[
          'Privy capture pairing — not Drip replacement — when list growth still needs popups feeding Sequenzy or Klaviyo post-Drip exit.',
        ]} />
      </section>

      <div class="container mb-12 max-w-4xl card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-slate-950">Pricing vs Drip</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>~10k people</th><th>~25k people</th><th>Model</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Drip</td><td>$89–149</td><td>$184–350</td><td>People in account</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sequenzy</td><td>$19–79</td><td>$49–149</td><td>Per email</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Klaviyo</td><td>$150–200</td><td>$350–450</td><td>Active profiles</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Omnisend</td><td>$60–100</td><td>$120–180</td><td>Contacts</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Brevo</td><td>$25–65</td><td>$50–120</td><td>Email volume</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="container max-w-4xl pb-8 text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-slate-950">Related</p>
        <p class="mt-2"><a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-drip">Sequenzy vs Drip</a> · <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-drip">Klaviyo vs Drip</a> · <a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-drip">Omnisend vs Drip</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  
  <section class="container pb-12">
    <article class="prose-shopify max-w-4xl card">
      <h2>Operator handbook: migration sequencing</h2>
      <p>Export consent timestamps, SMS opt-in source, and global suppressions before disconnecting the old platform. Rebuild welcome and cart first — they touch the highest-intent customers and expose integration gaps fastest. Run parallel sends only with explicit exclusion rules; overlapping abandonment or welcome messages are the fastest way to lose deliverability and customer trust during a transition.</p>
      <p>Model twelve-month cost at your expected send volume, not just today's contact count. Profile-based billing punishes list bloat; pay-per-email rewards engagement discipline. Assign one weekly owner to review revenue per recipient, margin after discounts, and unsubscribe rate on each migrated flow before you add winback or replenishment.</p>
      <h2>When to stay versus switch</h2>
      <p>Stay if the pain is operational — stale segments, missing suppressions, discount sprawl — and can be fixed with a two-week cleanup sprint. Switch when the platform cannot express your Shopify data model without CSV exports, when economics broke at your current scale, or when your team stopped editing flows because the UI tax is too high. The alternatives ranked on this page assume a genuine fit mismatch, not laziness.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first when lifecycle guidance and send-based economics are the bottleneck. Klaviyo remains the benchmark for native Shopify event depth and predictive segmentation. Omnisend fits teams wanting multichannel defaults quickly. Match the replacement to the failure mode named at the top of this guide — not to whichever logo your agency prefers.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  
      <article class="prose-shopify max-w-4xl card mt-12">
        <h2>Operator handbook: 30-day proof plan after you switch</h2>
        <p>Week one is infrastructure and trust: authenticate sending domains, verify Shopify webhooks, import only consented contacts, and run test profiles through welcome and cart paths. No broadcast campaigns until those pass. Week two launches welcome segmented by acquisition source — popup, checkout, landing page — with different offer policies per source. Measure first purchase within fourteen days and unsubscribe rate by branch.</p>
        <p>Week three adds cart recovery with inventory checks and recent-purchaser suppression. Compare recovery rate and margin after discount to your old platform baseline — not to vendor case studies. Week four introduces post-purchase or winback with a holdout group if list size allows. Document every suppression rule in a shared runbook so sale-week edits do not break other flows.</p>
        <h2>Questions to ask sales before you sign</h2>
        <p>Can we suppress recent purchasers across email and SMS in one rule? Can we branch welcome by collection interest from Shopify browse data? Can we cap discounts by cart value or customer LTV tier? Can we see revenue per flow and per segment weekly without exporting? Can we pause all promotional sends during DNS or deliverability incidents in one action? Weak answers predict the same pain you are leaving.</p>
        <p>Ask for migration support scope in writing: templates, segments, automations, DNS, and training hours. Ask what happens to SMS compliance records and historical consent on exit. Ask how billing scales at double the sends you project for month twelve. Operators who skip these questions often re-migrate eighteen months later.</p>
        <h2>How this page fits the rest of the handbook</h2>
        <p>Use <a class="link" href="/guides/migration">migration guide</a> for checklists, <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> for scoring, <a class="link" href="/compare">comparisons</a> for pairwise tests, and <a class="link" href="/use-cases">use-case playbooks</a> for workflow specs. This alternatives page names exit triggers and ranked replacements; the other routes teach you how to implement without duplicate sends or margin collapse.</p>
      </article>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Drip alternatives FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
